<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06136114 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06136114 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  EMPLOYMENT; MATH  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Mathematics may be an abstract science, and people who are good at it may havemore options in the work world than they realize, says the head of aconsulting and actuarial firm.;    &quot;Many people are unaware of the vocationalpossibilities for math majors,&quot; says Robert E. Pugh, senior vice president atBooke andamp; Co. He cites some of the top-ranked jobs in the country, which rely onmathematical skills: Actuary, computer programmer, computer systems analyst,mathematician and statistician.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Special Section  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  JOB OPTIONS MULTIPLY FOR MATH MAJORS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Spring Careers(Special Section)Science  </MEMO><TEXT>     The company has produced an 11-minute educational video, &quot;Aftermath,&quot; topoint up career opportunities for math majors. The video is available toteachers, librarians and school counselors without charge. Write toBusiness-Education Partnership Coordinator, Booke andamp; Co., P.O. Box 66,Winston-Salem, NC 27102.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Schaumburg, Ill.  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910515  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  11G  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  129  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday May 15, 199100136114,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>